{"title_page": "Cambridge Buskers", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Music|date=May 2012}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Cambridge Buskers''' were a duo of [[United Kingdom|British]] musicians, whose career began in the late 1970s and were subsequently called '''The Classic Buskers'''. They performed classical music humorously using many instruments, costumes and props.\n\n[[Michael Copley]] and [[David Adam Gillespie (Dag) Ingram]] met when they were students at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]].  According to the liner notes of their first recording, their musical association began when they found themselves at [[Blackfriars station]] without enough money for the fare to get home.  In an attempt to raise the money from passers-by, they played ''[[The Entertainer (rag)|The Entertainer]]'' and ''[[Eine kleine Nachtmusik]]'' for a while, until they were asked to leave by a [[London Regional Transport|London Transport]] official.\n\nSubsequently, they gained international success with their performances and many recordings, and performed in over 20 countries and in 15 languages until September 2016<ref>{{cite web|title=Diary - The Classic Buskers|url=https://classicbuskers.com/diary/|publisher=Michael Copley|accessdate=7 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208035316/https://classicbuskers.com/diary/|archive-date=8 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>, when they disbanded after an incident in Shanghai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slippedisc.com/2016/06/english-chorus-master-is-shamed-in-china-for-not-wearing-knickers/|title=English Chorus Master is shamed in Shanghai|accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref>  It is reported that at one point a [[Japanese language|Japanese]] comic strip was written about them.\n\nIan Moore (now known as [[Ian de Massini]]), another Cambridge University graduate who is also an organist, conductor, composer and singer (formerly in [[King's College Choir, Cambridge]]), was the accordionist for the latter part of the Buskers' history.\n\nThe Classic Buskers wrote their own arrangements, primarily of classical works by famous composers.  Ian Moore played [[accordion|piano accordion]], used his voice, and occasionally other percussion instruments or props.  Copley played a variety of woodwind instruments, including [[flute]], [[recorder (musical instrument)|recorder]], [[ocarina]], and [[crumhorn]].\n\n==Discography==\nSome of these LPs were released under different titles in different countries.\n\n*''A Little Street Music'' (1977)\n*''Between Pub & Podium'' (1977)\n*''Not Live From New York'' (1979)\n*''Another Serious Album'' (1981)\n*''Soap Opera'' (1982)\n*''Music Abbreviation 101'' (1983)\n*''The Cambridge Buskers Handel Bach'' (1985)\n*''The Explosive Sound of The Cambridge Buskers'' (1985)\n*''The Cambridge Buskers Collection'' (2007) [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] (Aust) Classics 480 0136 (4 CD compilation. Over 130 tracks, mostly from the above LPs)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170301092459/https://classicbuskers.com/ Official web site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150923195513/http://www.buywell.com/booklets/4800136.pdf Further information and photos]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:English pop music groups]]\n[[Category:English buskers]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from London]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Cambridge|*Buskers]]\n[[Category:English musical duos]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in the 1970s]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Music|date=May 2012}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Cambridge Buskers''' were a duo of [[United Kingdom|British]] musicians, whose career began in the late 1970s and were subsequently called '''The Classic Buskers'''. They performed classical music humorously using many instruments, costumes and props.\n\n[[Michael Copley]] and [[David Adam Gillespie (Dag) Ingram]] met when they were students at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]].  According to the liner notes of their first recording, their musical association began when they found themselves at the [[Blackfriars station]] without enough money for the fare to get home.  In an attempt to raise the money from passers-by, they played ''[[The Entertainer (rag)|The Entertainer]]'' and ''[[Eine kleine Nachtmusik]]'' for a while, until they were asked to leave by a [[London Regional Transport|London Transport]] official.\n\nSubsequently, they gained international success with their performances and many recordings, and performed in over 20 countries and in 15 languages until September 2016<ref>{{cite web|title=Diary - The Classic Buskers|url=https://classicbuskers.com/diary/|publisher=Michael Copley|accessdate=7 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208035316/https://classicbuskers.com/diary/|archive-date=8 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>, when they disbanded after an incident in Shanghai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slippedisc.com/2016/06/english-chorus-master-is-shamed-in-china-for-not-wearing-knickers/|title=English Chorus Master is shamed in Shanghai|accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref>  It is reported that at one point a [[Japanese language|Japanese]] comic strip was written about them.\n\nIan Moore (now known as [[Ian de Massini]]), another Cambridge University graduate who is also an organist, conductor, composer and singer (formerly in [[King's College Choir, Cambridge]]), was the accordionist for the latter part of the Buskers' history.\n\nThe Classic Buskers wrote their own arrangements, primarily of classical works by famous composers.  Ian Moore played [[accordion|piano accordion]], used his voice, and occasionally other percussion instruments or props.  Copley played a variety of woodwind instruments, including [[flute]], [[recorder (musical instrument)|recorder]], [[ocarina]], and [[crumhorn]].\n\n==Discography==\nSome of these LPs were released under different titles in different countries.\n\n*''A Little Street Music'' (1977)\n*''Between Pub & Podium'' (1977)\n*''Not Live From New York'' (1979)\n*''Another Serious Album'' (1981)\n*''Soap Opera'' (1982)\n*''Music Abbreviation 101'' (1983)\n*''The Cambridge Buskers Handel Bach'' (1985)\n*''The Explosive Sound of The Cambridge Buskers'' (1985)\n*''The Cambridge Buskers Collection'' (2007) [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] (Aust) Classics 480 0136 (4 CD compilation. Over 130 tracks, mostly from the above LPs)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170301092459/https://classicbuskers.com/ Official web site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150923195513/http://www.buywell.com/booklets/4800136.pdf Further information and photos]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:English pop music groups]]\n[[Category:English buskers]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from London]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Cambridge|*Buskers]]\n[[Category:English musical duos]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in the 1970s]]\n", "name_user": "Neil (London)", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed (incorrect) definite article before \"Blackfriars Station\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cambridge_Buskers"}
{"title_page": "List of Holocaust transports from Slovakia", "text_new": "{{short description|List of deportation transports from Slovakia during the Holocaust}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox event\n| title                    = Deportation of Jews from Slovakia\n| image                    = File:KZ Sere\u010f - Holocaust-Museum - Transportwaggon.jpg\n| image_upright=1.1 \n|image_alt=Photograph of a restored train car, with its sliding door open, used to transport Slovak Jews \n| caption                  =Restored train car used to transport Slovak Jews. S\u017d stands for [[Slovensk\u00e9 \u017deleznice]] (Slovak Railways).{{sfn|Oschlies|2007}}\n| date                     = 1942 and 1944\u20131945\n| location                 = [[Slovak State]], German-occupied Poland, [[Nazi Germany]]\n| type                     = \n| cause                    = \n| motive                   = \n| target                   = [[Slovak Jews]]\n| organisers               = Slovak State, Nazi Germany\n| participants             = \n| outcome                  = \n| reported deaths          = 57,000 (1942)<br>10,000 (1944\u20131945)<br>Total: 67,000\n| notes                    = \n}}\n{{redirect|Deportation of Jews from Slovakia|text=You may be looking for [[1938 deportation of Jews from Slovakia]] or [[The Holocaust in Slovakia]].}}\nDuring [[the Holocaust]], most of Slovakia's Jewish population was deported in two waves\u20141942 and 1944\u20131945. In 1942, there were two destinations: 18,746  Jews were deported in eighteen transports to [[Auschwitz concentration camp]] and another 39,000\u201340,000{{efn|name=Lublin}} were deported in thirty-eight transports to [[Majdanek concentration camp|Majdanek]] and [[Sobib\u00f3r extermination camp|Sobib\u00f3r extermination camps]] and various ghettos in the [[Lublin Reservation|Lublin district]] of the [[General Governorate]]. A total of 57,628 people were deported; only a few hundred returned. In 1944 and 1945, 13,500 Jews were deported to Auschwitz (8,000 deportees), with smaller numbers sent to the [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]], [[Ravensbr\u00fcck]], [[Bergen-Belsen]], and [[Theresienstadt]] concentration camps. Altogether, these deportations resulted in the deaths of around 67,000 of the 89,000 Jews living in Slovakia.\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Background ==\nIn the political crisis that followed the September 1938 [[Munich Agreement]],{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=843}} the conservative, [[ethnonationalist]] [[Slovak People\u2019s Party]]{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=19}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|p=5}} unilaterally declared a state of autonomy for Slovakia within [[First Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovakia]]. Slovak Jews, who numbered 89,000 in 1940, were targeted for persecution. In November 1938, 7,500 Jews (impoverished or without Slovak citizenship) were [[1938 deportations of Jews from Slovakia|deported to the Hungarian border]]. Although they were allowed to return within a few months, these deportations were a rehearsal for those to follow in 1942.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|pp=843\u2013844}}{{sfn|Johnson|2005|p=316}}\n{{Location map many\n| Slovakia\n| width       = \n| float       = \n| border      = \n| caption     = Selected mentioned locations in Slovakia\n| alt         = \n| relief      = yes\n| AlternativeMap = \n<!--first label/marker-->\n| label1      = [[Sere\u010f concentration camp|Sere\u010f]]\n| position1   =  \n| coordinates1=  {{coord|48|17|N|17|44|E}}\n<!--second label/marker-->\n| label2      = Patr\u00f3nka \n| position2   = bottom\n| coordinates2= {{coord|48.167365|N|17.078333|E}}\n<!--repeat as needed--><!-- \n|label3=[[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]]\n|coordinates3= {{coord|50|2|4.9884|N|19|10|30.2484|E}} -->\n|label4=\u017dilina \n|coordinates4={{coord|49|13|22|N|18|44|24|E}}\n|label5=Poprad\n|coordinates5={{coord|49|03|34|N|20|17|51|E}}\n|label6=Nov\u00e1ky\n|coordinates6={{coord|48|42|48|N|18|32|22|E}}\n|label7=\n}}\n\nOn 14 March 1939, the [[Slovak State]] declared independence with German support. Many Jews lost their jobs and property due to [[The Holocaust in Slovakia#Aryanization|Aryanization]], which resulted in large numbers of them becoming impoverished. This became a pressing social problem for the Slovak government, which it \"solved\" by deporting the unemployed Jews. Slovakia initially agreed with the German government to deport 20,000 Jews of working age to German-occupied Poland, paying Nazi Germany 500 Reichsmarks each (supposedly to  cover the cost of resettlement). However, this was only the first step in the deportation of all Jews, because deporting workers while leaving their families behind would worsen the economic situation of the remaining Jews.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|pp=843, 845\u2013847}}{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=324\u2013325}}\n\nIn the meantime, Nazi Germany had been working towards the [[Final Solution]]\u2014the murder of all the Jews that it could reach. In 1939, the [[Lublin District]] in [[German-occupied Poland]] was set aside as a \"Jewish reservation\". In 1942 it became a reception point for Jews from Nazi Germany and Slovakia. Starting in late 1941, the ''[[Schutzstaffel]]'' (SS) began planning  for the deportation of the Jews in Lublin to the [[Operation Reinhard]] death camps\u2014[[Be\u0142\u017cec extermination camp|Be\u0142\u017cec]], [[Sobib\u00f3r extermination camp|Sobib\u00f3r]] and [[Treblinka extermination camp|Treblinka]]\u2014to free up space for the Slovak and German Jews.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=294\u2013295}}\n\n==1942==\n{{see also|The Holocaust in Slovakia#Deportations}}\n\n===Initial phase===\n[[File:Linda Reich Auschwitz Album.jpg |thumb|upright=1.25|Linda Reich ''(center)'', deported on the [[First mass transport of Jews to Auschwitz concentration camp|first transport from Slovakia]], and other prisoners sort belongings confiscated from Jews deported from [[Carpathian Ruthenia]], 1944]]\nThe original deportation plan, approved in February 1942 by the German and Slovak governments, entailed the deportation of 7,000 single women aged 16\u201335 to [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] and 13,000 single men aged 16\u201345 to [[Majdanek concentration camp|Majdanek]] as forced laborers.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=324\u2013325}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=301}} The cover name for the operation was '''''Aktion David'''''.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=217}}{{sfn|Oschlies|2007}} The SS officer and ''[[Judenberater]]'' (adviser on Jewish issues) [[Dieter Wisliceny]] and Slovak officials promised that deportees would not be mistreated and would be allowed to return home after a fixed period.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=302}} Initially, many Jews believed that it was better to report for deportation than risk reprisals against their families for failing to do so.{{sfn|Bauer|2002|pp=177\u2013178}} However, 3,000 of the 7,000 women who were supposed to be deported refused to report as ordered. Methods of escape included sham marriages, being sent away to live with relatives, or being hidden temporarily by non-Jews. The [[Hlinka Guard]] struggled to meet its targets;{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|pp=302\u2013303}} as a result, only 3,800 women and 4,500 men were deported during the initial phase of deportations.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=325}} Nevertheless, they opened \"a new chapter in the history of the Holocaust\" because the Slovak women were the first Jewish prisoners in Auschwitz. Their arrival precipitated the conversion of the camp into an [[extermination camp]].{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|pp=306\u2013307}}\n\nDepartment 14, a subsidiary of Slovakia's Central Economic Office, organized the transports,{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=66}} while the Slovak Transport Ministry provided the [[Holocaust trains|cattle cars]].{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=777}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=230}} Members of the Hlinka Guard, the ''[[Freiwillige Schutzstaffel]]'' (FS) and the [[gendarmerie]] were in charge of rounding up the Jews, guarding the transit centers, and eventually loading them into overcrowded cattle cars for deportation.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=230}} Transports were timed to reach the Slovak border near [[\u010cadca]] at 04:28.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=874}}{{efn|Transports left [[Patr\u00f3nka]],{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=855}} [[Poprad]],{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=879}} and [[Nov\u00e1ky]] in the evening,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}} and [[\u017dilina]] at 03:20.{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=889}}}} In [[Zwardon]] at 08:30, the Hlinka Guard turned the transports over to the German {{lang|de|[[Schutzpolizei (Nazi Germany)|Schutzpolizei]]}}.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=32}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=294}} The transports would arrive in Auschwitz the same afternoon{{sfn|Ghert-Zand|2020}} and at Majdanek the next morning.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=294}}\n\nOn 25 March 1942, the [[First mass transport of Jews to Auschwitz concentration camp|first transport train]] left Poprad at 20:00.{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=879}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=304}} Before its departure, Wisliceny spoke to the deportees on the platform, saying that they would be allowed to return home after they finished the work that Germany had planned for them. The first deportees were unaware of what lay ahead and tried to be optimistic. According to survivors, songs in Hebrew and Slovak were sung as the first two transports of women to Auschwitz left the platforms.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|pp=304\u2013305}} Most of the Slovak Jewish women deported to Auschwitz in 1942 who survived the war were from the first two transports in March, because they were younger and stronger.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=308}} Those from eastern Slovakia were especially likely to be young, because most Jews from that area were [[Haredim]] and tended to marry young: more than half were aged 21 or younger. The women deported from [[Bratislava]] were older on average because they married later in life and some did not marry at all; only 40 percent were 21 or younger.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=304}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"auto\" style=\"text-align: left\"\n!Date\n!Source\n!Destination\n!Number of deportees\n|-\n|25\u201326 March{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=879}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=320}}\n|[[Poprad transit camp|Poprad]]\n|[[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]]\n|997{{sfn|Ghert-Zand|2020}}\n|- \n|27 March\n|[[\u017dilina transit camp|\u017dilina]]\n|[[Majdanek concentration camp|Majdanek]]\n|1000{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}}\n|- \n|27\u201328 March\n|[[Patr\u00f3nka transit camp|Patr\u00f3nka]]\n|Auschwitz\n|798,{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=320}}{{sfn|Czech |1997|p=150}} 1000,{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=180}} or 1002{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=855}}\n|-\n|28\u201330 March\n|[[Sere\u010f concentration camp|Sere\u010f]]\n|Majdanek\n|1000{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=881}}\n|-\n|30\u201331 March\n|[[Nov\u00e1ky concentration camp|Nov\u00e1ky]]\n|Majdanek\n|1003{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=874}}\n|- \n|1\u20132 April\n|Patr\u00f3nka\n|Auschwitz\n|965{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|pp=305, 320}}{{sfn|Czech|1997|p=152}}\n|- \n|2{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=879}}\u20133 April\n|Poprad\n|Auschwitz\n|997{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=320}}{{sfn|Czech|1997|p=153}}\n|-\n|5 April\n|\u017dilina\n|Majdanek\n|1495{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 8pt\"|Most information can also be verified to {{harvnb|Fatran|2007|p=180}}\n|}\n\n===Transports to Lublin===\n[[File:General Government camps of Lublin Reservation.png|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=A map showing the distribution of the campsof the Lublin Reservation | General Government camps of Lublin Reservation.]]\nSS leader [[Reinhard Heydrich]] visited Bratislava on 10 April 1942. He and [[Vojtech Tuka]] agreed that further deportations would target whole families and eventually remove all Jews from Slovakia.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=325\u2013326}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=222\u2013223}} Ostensibly, the change was to avoid separating families, but it also solved the problem of caring for the children and elderly family members of able-bodied deportees.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=230}} The family transports began on 11 April and took their victims to the Lublin district.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=325\u2013326}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=222\u2013223}} This change disrupted the SS's plans in the Lublin district. Instead of able-bodied male Slovak Jews being deported to Majdanek, the SS needed to prepare space for Slovak Jewish families in the region's overcrowded ghettos.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=325}}  The transports from Slovakia were the largest and longest of all the deportations of Jews to the Lublin District.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=294}}\n\nThe trains went through two railway distribution points, in [[Na\u0142\u0119cz\u00f3w]] and Lublin, where they were met by a ranking SS officer. In Lublin, there was usually a selection and able-bodied men were selected for labor at Majdanek, while the remainder were sent to ghettos along the rail lines. For the trains that went through Na\u0142\u0119cz\u00f3w, the Jews were dispatched to locations seeking forced labor, usually without separating families.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=295}} Most of the trains brought their victims (30,000 in total){{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=785}} to ghettos whose inhabitants had been recently deported to the Be\u0142\u017cec or Sobib\u00f3r death camps,{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=325}} as part of a \"revolving door\" policy in which foreign Jews were brought in to replace those murdered.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|pp=299, 301}} The final transports to the Lublin district occurred during the first half of June 1942; ten transports stopped briefly at Majdanek, where able-bodied men (generally those aged 15\u201350) were selected for labor; the trains continued to Sobib\u00f3r, where the remaining victims were murdered.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=325\u2013326}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|pp=159, 166}}\n\nThe victims were given only four hours warning to prevent them from escaping. Beatings and forcible beard shaving were commonplace, as was subjecting Jews to invasive searches to uncover hidden valuables.{{sfn|Sokolovi\u010d|2013|pp=346\u2013347}} Although some guards and local officials accepted bribes to keep Jews off the transports, the victim would typically be deported on the next train.{{sfn|Kamenec|2011b|p=107}} Others took advantage of their power to rape Jewish women.{{sfn|Sokolovi\u010d|2013|p=347}} Jews were only allowed to bring {{convert|50|kg}} of personal items with them, but even this was frequently stolen.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=66}} Official exemptions were supposed to keep Jews from being deported, but local authorities sometimes deported exemption holders.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|p=305}}\n\nMost groups stayed only briefly in the Lublin ghettos before they were deported again to the death camps, while a few remained in the ghettos for months or years.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=325\u2013326}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=296}} Several thousand of the deportees ended up in the forced-labor camps in the Lublin area (such as [[Poniatowa concentration camp|Poniatowa]], [[Ko\u0144skowola forced-labor camp|Ko\u0144skowola]], and [[Krych\u00f3w forced-labor camp|Krych\u00f3w]]).{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|pp=159, 161}} Unusually, the deportees in the Lublin area were quickly able to establish contact with the Jews remaining in Slovakia, which led to [[Working Group (resistance organization)#Aid to deportees|extensive aid efforts]].{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=160}} However, the fate of the Jews deported from Slovakia was ultimately \"sealed within the framework of Operation Reinhard\", along with that of the Polish Jews.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=153}} Of the estimated 8,500 men who were deported directly to Majdanek, only 883 were still alive by July 1943.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=325}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=159}} (Another few thousand Slovak Jews were deported to Majdanek following the liquidation of ghettos in the Lublin district, but most of them were murdered immediately.){{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=159}} The remaining Slovak Jews at Majdanek were shot during [[Operation Harvest Festival]]; the only significant group of Slovak Jews to remain in Lublin district was a group of about 100 at the ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' camp in [[D\u0119blin\u2013Irena Ghetto#Luftwaffe camp|D\u0119blin\u2013Irena]].{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|pp=159\u2013160}}\n\n{{clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable   sortable\" width=\"auto\" style=\"text-align: left\"\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 100px;\" | Date\n!Source\n!Destination\n!Secondary destination\n!Number of deportees\n!class=unsortable|Notes\n|-\n|11{{sfn|Kamenec |2007|p=222}}\u201313 April{{sfn|Kuwa\u0142ek|2012|p=673}}\n|[[Trnava]]\n|[[Lubart\u00f3w Ghetto|Lubart\u00f3w]]/Majdanek\n|Kamionka, Firlej\n|1040\n|rowspan=\"2\"| About 900 Jews arrived in Lubart\u00f3w from the first transport and 680 from the second. They were soon transferred elsewhere, mostly to Firlej and Ostr\u00f3w.{{sfn|Kuwa\u0142ek|2012|pp=673\u2013674}}\n|-\n|14{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}}\u201315 April{{sfn|Kuwa\u0142ek|2012|p=673}}\n|[[Nitra]]\n|Lubart\u00f3w/Majdanek\n|Ostr\u00f3w Lubelski\n|1038\n|-\n|16{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=180}}\u201317 April{{sfn|Dean|2012|p=704}}\n|Nitra\n|Rejowiec/Majdanek\n|[[Trawniki concentration camp|Trawniki]]\n|1048\n|About 840 Jews arrived in Rejowiec.{{sfn|Dean|2012|p=704}}\n|-\n|20 April{{sfn|Dean|2012|p=704}}\n|Nitra\n|Rejowiec\n|\n|1030\n|\n|-\n|21{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=881}}\u201322 April{{sfn|Crago|White|2012|p=689}}\n|[[Topo\u013e\u010dany]]/Sere\u010f\n|Opole\n|\n|1001\n|rowspan=\"2\"| From the five transports to Opole (totaling 4,302 deportees), only 1,400 Jews remained in the ghetto; the remainder were sent to labor camps in the area.{{sfn|Crago|White|2012|p=689}}\n|-\n|27 April\n|[[Nov\u00e9 Mesto nad V\u00e1hom]], [[Pie\u0161\u0165any]], and [[Hlohovec]]\n|Opole\n|[[Poniatowa concentration camp|Poniatowa]]\n|1179\u20131382{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|pp=296\u2013297}}\n|-\n|5{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}}\u20137 May{{sfn|Kuwa\u0142ek|2012|p=673}}\n|[[Trebi\u0161ov]]\n|Lubart\u00f3w/Majdanek\n|Kamionka\n|1040\n|841 Slovak Jews arrived in Lubart\u00f3w.{{sfn|Kuwa\u0142ek|2012|p=673}}\n|-\n|6{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}}\u20138 May{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=679}}\n|[[Michalovce]]\n|\u0141uk\u00f3w\n|\n|1038\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Slovak Jews remained at \u0141uk\u00f3w until the ghetto's liquidation on 2 May 1943.{{sfn|Crago|2012|pp=680\u2013681}}\n|-\n|7{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}}\u20139 May{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=679}}\n|Michalovce\n|\u0141uk\u00f3w\n|\n|1040\n|-\n|8 May\n|Michalovce\n|[[Mi\u0119dzyrzec Podlaski Ghetto|Mi\u0119dzyrzec Podlaski]]\n|\n|1001{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}} or 1,025{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=684}}\n|\n|-\n|11 May{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=624}}\n|[[Humenn\u00e9]]\n|Che\u0142m\n|\n|1009\n|rowspan=\"2\"| The SS confiscated the deportees' luggage. Some were conscripted to work for the {{lang|de|Wasserwirtschaftsinspektion}} (Water Regulation Authority) at Siedliszcze. Others were deported to [[Sobib\u00f3r extermination camp]] on 22\u201323 May. The ghetto was liquidated on 5\u20139 November 1942.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=624}}\n|-\n|12 May{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=624}}\n|\u017dilina\n|Che\u0142m\n|\n|1002\n|-\n|13 May{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}\n|[[Pre\u0161ov]]\n|[[D\u0119blin\u2013Irena Ghetto|D\u0119blin\u2013Irena]]\n|\n|1040\n|rowspan=\"2\"|On 15 October 1942, most of the Slovak Jews were deported to [[Treblinka extermination camp]].{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}} About a hundred Slovak Jewish men and women\u2014the last significant group of Slovak Jews to survive in the Lublin area\u2014were kept by the [[Luftwaffe]] to work as forced laborers on the nearby airfield. On 22 July 1944, they were sent to [[Cz\u0119stochowa]] where a few dozen managed to survive until the liberation.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=159}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=77}}{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}\n|-\n|14 May{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}\n|Pre\u0161ov\n|D\u0119blin\u2013Irena\n|\n|1040\n|-\n|17{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}}\u201320 May{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=655}}\n|[[Bardejov]]\n|Ko\u0144skowola{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=655}}\n|\n| 1,025{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=655}} or 1028\n|rowspan=\"4\"|The first transport to Ko\u0144skowola included 700 elderly individuals and children.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=655}} The second arrived before 2 June. At Ko\u0144skowola, Slovak Jews were employed in agricultural labor and suffered from severe hunger. In early October, the ghetto was liquidated. Except for 500 to 1,000 craftsmen who were deported to labor camps in the area, the remaining Jews were shot, either during the roundups or in ravines near [[Rudy, Lublin Voivodeship|Rudy]].{{sfn|Crago|2012|pp=655\u2013656}}\n|-\n|18 May\n|Bardejov\n|Opole\n|Poniatowa\n|1015\n|-\n|19 May\n|[[Vranov nad Top\u013eou|Vranov]]\n|Opole\n|Kazimierz\n|1005\n|-\n|20 May\n|[[Medzilaborce]]\n|Ko\u0144skowola{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=655}}\n|\n|1001{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}} or 1,630{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=655}}\n|-\n|23 or 27 May{{sfn|Dean|2012|p=704}}\n|[[Sabinov]]/Pre\u0161ov\n|Rejowiec\n|\n|1630\n|rowspan=\"3\"|At Rejowiec, some Slovak Jews worked for the [[Jewish Ghetto Police]]. Either in June or August 1942, 2,000 mostly Slovak Jews were rounded up and deported to Sobib\u00f3r; some 50\u2013100 were taken out of the lines at Sobib\u00f3r and sent to nearby [[Krych\u00f3w forced-labor camp]].{{sfn|Dean|2012|pp=704\u2013705}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=158}}\n|-\n|24 or 28 May{{sfn|Dean|2012|p=704}}\n|[[Stropkov]]/Bardejov\n|Rejowiec\n|\n|1022\n|-\n|24{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=879}}\u201325 May{{sfn|Dean|2012|p=704}}\n|Poprad\n|Rejowiec\n|\n|1000\n|-\n|25{{sfn|Crago|White|2012|p=689}} or 26 May to 30 May{{sfn |Yad Vashem |2009|p=552}}\n|\u017dilina\n|Opole\n|\n|1000\n|\n|-\n|29 May{{sfn|Kuwa\u0142ek|Dean|2012|p=641}}\n|[[Spi\u0161sk\u00e1 Nov\u00e1 Ves]]\n|[[Izbica Ghetto|Izbica]]/Majdanek\n|\n|1032{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}} or 1052{{sfn|Kuwa\u0142ek|Dean|2012|p=641}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|At Izbica, Jews were held temporarily under extremely overcrowded conditions before being deported to [[Be\u0142\u017cec extermination camp]] and Sobib\u00f3r.{{sfn|Kuwa\u0142ek|Dean|2012|pp=640\u2013642}}\n|-\n|29{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=879}}\u201330 May{{sfn|Kuwa\u0142ek|Dean|2012|p=641}}\n|Poprad\n|Izbica/Majdanek\n|\n|1000\n|-\n|30 May{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=879}}\u20131 June\n|Poprad\n|[[Sobib\u00f3r extermination camp|Sobib\u00f3r]]/Majdanek\n|\n|1000\n|rowspan=\"10\"|These transports were the only ones that went directly from Slovakia to one of the [[Operation Reinhard]] extermination camps. They signified the end of the \"revolving door\", as German policy shifted from temporarily warehousing Jews deported to Poland in ghettos to murdering them immediately.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=325\u2013326, 358}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|pp=296, 301\u2013302}}\n|-\n|2 June\n|[[Liptovsk\u00fd Sv\u00e4t\u00fd Mikul\u00e1\u0161]]\n|Sobib\u00f3r/Majdanek\n|\n|1014\n|-\n|5 June\n|[[Bratislava]]/\u017dilina\n|Sobib\u00f3r/Majdanek\n|\n|1000\n|-\n|8 June\n|\u017dilina\n|Sobib\u00f3r/Majdanek\n|\n|1001\n|-\n|7 June\n|Bratislava/\u017dilina\n|Sobib\u00f3r/Majdanek\n|\n|1000\n|-\n|9 June\n|[[Zvolen]]/[[Kremnica]]\n|Sobib\u00f3r/Majdanek\n|\n|1019\n|-\n|11 June\n|Nov\u00e1ky\n|Sobib\u00f3r/Majdanek\n|\n|1000\n|-\n|12 June\n|Sere\u010f/\u017dilina\n|Sobib\u00f3r/Majdanek\n|\n|1000\n|-\n|12{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=879}}\u201313 June\n|Poprad\n|Sobib\u00f3r/Majdanek\n|\n|1000\n|-\n|14 June\n|Nov\u00e1ky/\u017dilina\n|Sobib\u00f3r/Majdanek\n|\n|1000\n|- \n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 8pt\"| Where two primary destinations are listed, there was a selection in Lublin and able-bodied men (generally those aged 15\u201350 years) were sent to Majdanek.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|pp=159, 166}}  All information from {{harvnb|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=166}} unless otherwise indicated. Most information can also be verified to {{harvnb|Fatran|2007|p=180}}; {{harvnb|Silberklang|2013|pp=303\u2013306}}.\n|}\n\n===Transports to Auschwitz===\nA moratorium on transports to the east was imposed on 19 June 1942 due to military campaigns on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]. The rest of the family transports (eight in total) were therefore directed to Auschwitz. The first arrived on 4 July,{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=333\u2013334}} which led to the initial selection on the ramp at [[Auschwitz II-Birkenau]], which became a regular event. The majority of deportees\u2014especially mothers with children\u2014were not chosen for forced labor and instead were killed in gas chambers.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=313}}{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=326, 345}} By 1 August, most of the Jews not exempt from deportation had already been deported or had fled to Hungary to avoid the deportations, leading to a six-week halt in the transports.{{sfn|Bauer |1994|p=97}} An additional three trains departed for Auschwitz in September and October.{{sfn |Kamenec |2007|p=247}}\n\nFor the first three months after the arrival of the first transport in March, Slovak Jewish women were the only female Jewish prisoners in Auschwitz.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=308}} In mid-August, most of the Slovak Jewish women at Auschwitz were transferred to Auschwitz II-Birkenau,{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=308}} which was still under construction. Conditions were much worse;{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=313}} employed mostly on outdoor labor details, most of the women died within the first four months at Birkenau.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=309}} Along with backbreaking physical labor and starvation, many died in epidemics of [[typhus]] or [[malaria]] and the mass executions ordered by the SS to contain the epidemics. (To contain a typhus epidemic in October 1942, the SS murdered 6,000 prisoners\u2014mostly Slovak Jewish women\u2014including some who were healthy; another selection on 5 December eliminated the last major group of Slovak Jewish women in Birkenau.){{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|pp=313\u2013314}} Of the 404 men who were registered on 19 June, only 45 were still alive six weeks later.{{sfn|Friling|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GLM0MF5ZPrQC&pg=PT113 113]}} By the end of 1942, 92% of the deportees had died. This left only 500 or 600 Slovak Jews still alive at Auschwitz and its [[subcamp (SS)|subcamps]]{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=34}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|pp=309, 322}}\u2014about half of whom had obtained privileged positions in administration which allowed them to obtain the necessities for survival.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=316}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"auto\" style=\"text-align: left\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Source\n!Women registered\n!Men registered\n!Murdered in gas chambers\n!Total\n!class=unsortable|Notes\n|- \n|12\u201313 April\n|Sere\u010f{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=881}}{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=180}}\n|443\n|634\n|\n|1077\n|rowspan=\"5\" |These transports contained single men and women as well as childless couples.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=307}}\n|- \n|17 April\n|\u017dilina{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=180}}\n|27\n|973\n|\n|1000\n|- \n|19 April\n|\u017dilina{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=180}}\n|536\n|46\n|\n|1000\n|- \n|22\u201323 April\n|Poprad{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=879}}{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=180}}\n|457\n|543\n|\n|1000\n|- \n|24 April\n|\u017dilina{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=180}}\n|558\n|442\n|\n|1000\n|- \n|29 April\n|\u017dilina{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=180}}\n|300\n|423\n|300\n|1054\n|rowspan=\"2\" |These two transports had to be supplemented with families with children to meet the quota.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=307}}\n|- \n|19\u201320 June\n|\u017dilina{{sfn|Friling|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=GLM0MF5ZPrQC&pg=PT113 113]}}\n|255\n|404\n|341\n|1000\n|-\n|3\u20134 July\n|\u017dilina{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}}\n|108\n|264\n|628\n|1000\n|This was the first family transport to Auschwitz, the first selection ever on the ramp at Birkenau, and the first group to be murdered in Bunker II.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=307}}{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=326, 345}}\n|-\n|10\u201311 July\n|\u017dilina{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}}\n|148\n|182\n|670\n|1000\n|\n|-\n|16{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}}\u201318 July\n|\u017dilina{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}}\n|178\n|327\n|459\n|1000\n|\n|-\n|24\u201325 July\n|\u017dilina{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}}\n|93\n|192\n|715\n|1000\n|\n|-\n|31 July\u20131 August\n|\u017dilina{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}}\n|75\n|165\n|608\n|848\n|By 1 August, most of the Jews not exempt from deportation had already been deported or had fled to Hungary, leading to a six-week halt in the transports.{{sfn|Bauer |1994|p=97}}\n|-\n|19 September\n|\u017dilina{{sfn |Kamenec |2007|p=247}}\n|71\n|206\n|723\n|1000\n|rowspan=\"3\" |  The final transports targeted Jews in the labor camps, especially those who were mentally or physically disabled.{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p= 171}}  \n|-\n|23 September\n|\u017dilina{{sfn |Kamenec |2007|p=247}}\n|67\n|294\n|639\n|1000\n|-\n|20\u201321 October\n|\u017dilina{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=889}}{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}}\n|78\n|121\n|649\n|848 (or 860){{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 8pt\"|All information from {{harvnb|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=320}} except source locations, from {{harvnb|Fatran|2007|pp=180\u2013181}}. Most of it can also be verified to {{harvnb|Czech |1997|pp=154, 157\u2013160, 184, 191\u2013192, 196, 199, 203, 208, 241, 243, 256}}. \n|}\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:Fragment listy transportowej z \u017biliny do Sobiboru czerwiec 1942.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph of a list of twenty Jews deported from \u017dilina to the Sobib\u00f3r extermination camp dated 14 June 1942| List of Jews deported from \u017dilina to [[Sobib\u00f3r extermination camp]], 14 June 1942]]\nBetween 25 March and 20 October 1942, about 57,700{{efn|Estimates include 57,628{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}} and 57,752.{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=82}}}} Jews (two-thirds of the population) were deported.{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=69}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=189}}  Sixty-three of the deportation trains from Slovakia were organized by [[Franz Novak]].{{sfn|Browning|2007|p=381}} The deportations disproportionately affected poor, rural, and Orthodox Jews; although the \u0160ari\u0161-Zempl\u00edn region in eastern Slovakia lost 85 to 90 percent of its Jewish population, \u017dilina reported that almost half of its Jews remained after the deportation.{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=584}} The deportees were held briefly in camps in Slovakia before deportation; 26,384 from \u017dilina,{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=889}} 7,500 from Patr\u00f3nka,{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=855}} 7,000 from Poprad,{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=879}} 4,160{{sfn|Danko|2010|p=13}} (or 4,463){{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=882}} from Sere\u010f, and 4,000 to 5,000 from Nov\u00e1ky.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=876}} Eighteen trains with 18,746 victims{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=785}} went to Auschwitz, and another thirty-eight transports (with 39,000 to 40,000 deportees){{efn|name=Lublin|Estimates include 39,006 (Katar\u00edna Hradsk\u00e1),{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=82}} 39,875 (Gila Fatran), 39,883 ([[Yehoshua B\u00fcchler]]),{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=296}} or 39,899 passengers (Laura Crago{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=608}} and Janina Kie\u0142bo\u0144). The exact number is unknown and impossible to determine due to discrepancies in the sources. For example, some Jews died or committed suicide before they were deported or during transport and were not counted consistently.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|pp=296\u2013297}}}} went to ghettos and concentration and extermination camps in the Lublin district.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=151}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}} Only a few hundred (estimated at 250{{sfn|Rothkirchen|2001|p=598}} or 800{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=235}}) survived the war.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2002|p=130}} Czech historian Daniel Put\u00edk estimates that only 1.5 percent (around 280 people) of those deported to Auschwitz in 1942 survived, while the death rate of those deported to the Lublin region approached 100 percent.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=47}}\n\nAttempts by Germany and Slovak People's Party radicals to resume the transports in 1943 were unsuccessful due to the opposition of Slovak moderates and were followed by a [[The Holocaust in Slovakia#Hiatus (1943)|two-year hiatus]].{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=848}}{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=404\u2013405}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==1944\u20131945 {{anchor|1944}}==\n{{see also|The Holocaust in Slovakia#Resumption of deportations}}\n[[File:Selection on the ramp at Auschwitz II-Birkenau, 1944 (Auschwitz Album) 3a.jpg|left| |thumb|alt= A photograph shows hundreds of men and women in two lines on a platform beside two railroad lines. Another line of prisoners has formed on the opposite side of the tracks. |A selection on the ramp at [[Auschwitz II-Birkenau]] in 1944 (from the [[Auschwitz Album]])]]\nIncreasing [[Slovak partisan]] activity triggered a German invasion on 29 August 1944. The partisans responded by launching a full-scale [[Slovak National Uprising|uprising]]. The insurgents seized a large portion of central Slovakia but were defeated by the end of October.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=849}} [[Einsatzgruppe H]], one of the [[Einsatzgruppen|SS death squads]], was formed to deport or murder the estimated 25,000 Jews remaining in Slovakia.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|pp=99, 101}} Einsatzgruppe H was aided by local collaborators, including [[SS-Heimatschutz Slowakei|SS-Heimatschutz]], [[Abwehrgruppe 218]], and the [[Hlinka Guard Emergency Divisions]].{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=101}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|pp=41\u201342}} Most of the Jews who were exempted from the 1942 deportations lived in western Slovakia,{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=90}} but following the invasion many fled to the mountains.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p= 99}}\n\nSlovak historian [[Ivan Kamenec]] estimated that 13,500 Jews were deported, of whom 10,000 died,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=849}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=337}}{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=589}} but Israeli historian Gila Fatran and Czech historian [[Lenka \u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1]] consider that 14,150 deportees can be verified and the true figure may be higher.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013|p=82}}{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=119}} Of these, between 6,734 and 7,936 were deported to Auschwitz{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=47}} and another 5,000 to [[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp|Ravensbr\u00fcck]], [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]], [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]], and [[Theresienstadt Ghetto|Theresienstadt]]. From Slovakia, Ravensbr\u00fcck received transports totaling 1,600 women and children (mostly Jews) and 478 male prisoners, including Jews, [[Romani people]], and political opponents. About 1,550 to 1,750 men (mostly Jews) were deported to Sachsenhausen, while about 200\u2013300 people were deported from Sere\u010f to Bergen-Belsen, especially Jews in mixed marriages and some intact families of Jews. Between 1,454  and 1,467 Jews were deported to Theresienstadt, especially the elderly, orphans, and women with young children.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=203}} About 200 or 300 Slovak political prisoners were deported to [[Mauthausen concentration camp|Mauthausen]] on 19 January and 31 March 1945.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|pp=45, 47}} Many of those deported to the concentration camps in Germany were sent onwards to subcamps of the main camps, where they worked mostly in war industries.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=199}} On four transports from Sere\u010f, selections were carried out at the camp with different cars being directed to Sachsenhausen, Bergen-Belsen, Ravensbr\u00fcck, and/or Theresienstadt.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=203}} Many details of the transports are unknown, because much of the documentation was destroyed by the perpetrators, requiring historians to rely on survivor testimonies.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=116}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=337}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|pp=197, 212}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable  sortable\" width=\"auto\" style=\"text-align: left\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Source\n!Destination\n!Number of deportees\n!class=unsortable|Notes\n|-\n|1 September\n|[[\u010cadca]]\n|[[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]]\n|100+\n|Six men and eight women were registered at the camp. 72 males and an unknown number of females were sent to the gas chambers.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=117}}\n|-\n|5 September\n|\u010cadca\n|Auschwitz\n|\n|One man and two women were registered at the camp. An unknown number were sent to the gas chambers.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=117}}\n|-\n|20 September\n|Unknown\n|Auschwitz\n|177\n|From this transport, 146 people were sent to the gas chambers and the remainder were registered.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=117}} Israeli historian Gila Fatran estimates a total of 400 Jews were deported on the three transports.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=119}}\n|-\n|30 September\n|[[Sere\u010f concentration camp|Sere\u010f]]\n|Auschwitz\n|1860\n|{{sfn|Fatran|1996|pp=108,  118}}{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=92}}\n|-\n|3 October\n|Sere\u010f\n|Auschwitz\n|1836\n|{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=118}}{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=92}}\n|-\n|10{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=118}}\u201312 October{{sfn|Czech |1997|p=730}}\n|Sere\u010f\n|Auschwitz\n|1882 or 1890 \n|{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=118}}{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=92}}\n|-\n|17{{sfn|Fatran|1996|pp=112, 118}}\u201319 October{{sfn|Czech |1997|p=735}}\n|Sere\u010f\n|Auschwitz\n|862 or 920{{sfn|Fatran|1996|pp=112, 118}}{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=92}}\n|113 Jewish women were registered.{{sfn|Czech |1997|p=735}}\n|-\n|2 November\n|Sere\u010f\n|Auschwitz\n|920 or 930\n|The gas chambers of Auschwitz were used for the last time on the previous day. All of the deportees were registered at the camp without a selection.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=118}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|pp=55, 197\u2013198}}{{sfn|Czech|1997|pp=743\u2013744}}\n|-\n|2\u20133 November\n|Pre\u0161ov\n|[[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp|Ravensbr\u00fcck]]\n|364\n|Mostly Jews, some Romani people.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=68}} According to Fatran, about 100 Jews in total were deported from Pre\u0161ov.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=119}}\n|-\n|9 November\n|[[Ilava]]\n|Germany\n|183\n|This transport included Jews but the prisoners were predominantly non-Jewish. According to a German official, another transport with 100 individuals had been dispatched from Ilava the previous week, and also sent to Germany.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=117}} According to Fatran, the total number of Jews deported from Ilava was about 100.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=119}}\n|-\n|{{circa|15 November}}\n|Sere\u010f\n|Ravensbr\u00fcck\n|488\n|Jews{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=68}}\n|-\n|16 November\n|Sere\u010f\n|[[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]], [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]]\n|600\u2013800 (Sachsenhausen), 100\u2013200 (Bergen-Belsen)\n|Mostly Jews; there were some ''[[Mischlinge]]'' sent to Bergen-Belsen{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=68}}\n|-\n|28 November\n|Pre\u0161ov\n|Ravensbr\u00fcck\n|53\n|Women and children, mostly Jewish{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=69}}\n|-\n|2\u20133 December\n|Sere\u010f\n|Sachsenhausen, Ravensbr\u00fcck, [[Theresienstadt Ghetto|Theresienstadt]]\n| about 580 (Sachsenhausen), 160\u2013200 (Ravensbr\u00fcck),{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=69}} 416{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=93}} or 421 (Theresienstadt){{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=69}}\n|Jews and several political prisoners were sent to Sachsenhausen; the transport to Ravensbr\u00fcck consisted of Jewish women; those sent to Theresienstadt were exclusively Jews.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=69}} According to Slovak historian Katar\u00edna Hradsk\u00e1, the transport arrived in Theresienstadt on 23 December; 382 of those deported to Theresienstadt survived.{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=93}}\n|-\n|{{circa|10 January}}\n|[[Ke\u017emarok]]\n|Ravensbr\u00fcck\n|47 \n|Women and children, mostly Jews and some Romani people; also some political prisoners.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=69}}\n|-\n|16 January\n|Sere\u010f\n|Sachsenhausen, Ravensbr\u00fcck, Theresienstadt\n|370 (Sachsenhausen), 260\u2013310 (Ravensbr\u00fcck), 127{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=69}} or 129{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=93}} (Theresienstadt)\n|Sent to Sachsenhausen were Jewish men and political prisoners; Jewish women were sent to Ravensbr\u00fcck; the Jews sent to Theresienstadt were mostly those incapable of work{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=69}} The transport arrived in Theresienstadt 19 January and 127 of the 129 deportees survived.{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=93}}\n|-\n|9\u201312 March\n|Sere\u010f\n|Theresienstadt\n|548\n|According to Hradsk\u00e1, there were 546 survivors.{{sfn|Terez\u00edn Initiative|2016}}{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=118}}{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=93}}\n|-\n|31 March\u20137 April\n|Sere\u010f\n|Theresienstadt\n|354\n|According to Hradsk\u00e1, there were 352 survivors.{{sfn|Terez\u00edn Initiative|2016}}{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=118}}{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=93}}\n|}\n\nAn estimated 10,000 of the deportees died.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=337}} The mortality rate was highest on the transports to Auschwitz in September and October, because there was a selection and most of the deportees were immediately murdered in the gas chambers. The death rate of those deported to concentration camps in Germany was around 25\u201350 percent. Of those deported to the Theresienstadt Ghetto, however, 98 percent survived.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|pp=47, 212}} The high death rate at concentration camps such as Sachsenhausen, Bergen-Belsen and Ravensbr\u00fcck was due to the exploitation of forced labor for [[total war]] and inmates were murdered based on their inability to work, rather than their race or religion. Others died during the [[death marches (Holocaust)|death marches]].{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|pp=209\u2013210}} Between several hundred{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=849}} and 2,000{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=119}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=253}} Jews were killed in Slovakia, and about 10,850 survived to be liberated by the Red Army in March and April 1945.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=119}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=341}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable  sortable\" width=\"auto\" style=\"text-align: left\"\n|-\n!Destination\n!Killed\n!Total\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]]\n|Most\n|6,734\u20137,936\n|\n|-\n|[[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]]\n|30\u201350 percent\n|200\u2013300\n|Very few of the children deported to Bergen-Belsen survived.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=200}}\n|-\n|[[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp|Ravensbr\u00fcck]]\n|Less than 30 percent\n|About 2,000\n|\n|-\n| [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]]\n|At least 25 percent\n|1,550\u20131,750\n|\n|-\n|[[Theresienstadt Ghetto|Theresienstadt]]\n|2 percent (40 people{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=93}})\n|1,454\u20131,467\n|Hradsk\u00e1 attributes the deaths to [[natural causes]]{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|1996|p=93}}\n|-\n|Not deported\n|Several hundred{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=849}} to 2,000{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=119}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=253}}\n|10,850 survived{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=119}}\n|\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 8pt\"|All information from {{harvnb|Put\u00edk|2015|p=47}} unless otherwise indicated.\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n===Sources===\n====Books====\n{{refbegin|35em|indent=yes}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bauer |first1=Yehuda |authorlink=Yehuda Bauer |title=Jews for Sale?: Nazi-Jewish Negotiations, 1933\u20131945 |date=1994 |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=978-0-300-05913-7 |ref=harv |language=en |location=New Haven |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/jewsforsalenazij00baue }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Bauer |first1=Yehuda |title=Rethinking the Holocaust |date=2002 |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=978-0-300-09300-1 |ref=harv |language=en |location=New Haven }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Browning |first1=Christopher R.|authorlink=Christopher R. Browning |title=The Origins of the Final Solution: The Evolution of Nazi Jewish Policy, September 1939 \u2013 March 1942 |date=2007 |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |location=Lincoln |isbn=978-0-8032-0392-1 |ref=harv |language=en}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Czech |first1=Danuta |authorlink1=Danuta Czech |title=Auschwitz Chronicle, 1939-1945 |date=1997 |publisher=[[Henry Holt and Company|H. Holt]] |location=New York |isbn=978-0-8050-5238-1 |ref=harv |language=en}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Fatran |first1=Gila |title=Boj o pre\u017eitie|trans-title=The Struggle  for Survival |date=2007 |publisher=SNM - M\u00fazeum \u017didovskej Kult\u00fary |location=Bratislava |isbn=978-80-8060-206-2 |ref=harv |language=sk}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Friling |first1=Tuvia |authorlink1=Tuvia Friling |title=Secret Intelligence and the Holocaust: Collected Essays from the Colloquium at the City University of New York Graduate Center |date=2006 |publisher=Enigma Books |location=New York |isbn=978-1-929631-60-5 |pages=105\u2013156 |ref=harv |language=English |chapter=Istanbul  1942-1945:  The  Kollek-Avriel  and  Berman-Ofner Networks}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Hilberg |first1=Raul |authorlink1=Raul Hilberg |title=The Destruction of the European Jews |date=2003 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=978-0-300-09592-0 |ref=harv |language=en|volume=2|edition=3|orig-year=1961|title-link=The Destruction of the European Jews }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Hutzelmann |first1=Barbara |editor1-last=Hutzelmann |editor1-first=Barbara|editor2-last=Hausleitner |editor2-first=Mariana |editor3-last=Hazan  |editor3-first=Souzana|title=Slowakei, Rum\u00e4nien und Bulgarien|trans-title=Slovakia, Romania, and Bulgaria |date=2018 |publisher=[[Institut f\u00fcr Zeitgeschichte]] |location=Munich |isbn=978-3-11-036500-9 |language=de| series={{ill|Die Verfolgung und Ermordung der europ\u00e4ischen Juden durch das nationalsozialistische Deutschland 1933-1945|de}} [The Persecution and Murder of European Jews by Nazi Germany 1933-1945]|volume=13 |chapter=Einf\u00fchrung: Slowakei |trans-chapter=Introduction: Slovakia|ref=harv|pp=18\u201345}}\n*{{cite conference|last=Kamenec|first=Ivan|authorlink=Ivan Kamenec |chapter=The Deportation of Jewish Citizens from Slovakia in 1942 |pp=111\u2013139|editor1-last=D\u0142ugoborski|editor1-first=Wac\u0142aw|editor2-last=T\u00f3th |editor2-first=Dezider |editor3-last=Teresa|editor3-first=\u015awiebocka|editor4-last=Mensfelt|editor4-first=Jarek|translator-last=Mensfeld|translator-first=Jarek|title=The Tragedy of the Jews of Slovakia 1938\u20131945: Slovakia and the \"Final Solution of the Jewish Question\"|origyear=1992 |date =2002|publisher=Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum and Museum of the Slovak National Uprising|location= O\u015bwi\u0119cim and Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica |language=en|ref=harv|isbn=978-83-88526-15-2}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Kamenec |first1=Ivan|translator1-last=Styan |translator1-first=Martin |title=On the Trail of Tragedy: The Holocaust in Slovakia |date=2007 |publisher=Hajko & Hajkov\u00e1 |location=Bratislava |isbn=978-80-88700-68-5 |ref=harv |language=en|orig-year=1991}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Kamenec |first1=Ivan|chapter=The Slovak state, 1939\u20131945 |editor1-last=Teich |editor1-first=Mikul\u00e1\u0161 |editorlink=Mikul\u00e1\u0161 Teich|editor2-last=Kov\u00e1\u010d |editor2-first=Du\u0161an |editor2-link=Du\u0161an Kov\u00e1\u010d |editor3-last=Brown |editor3-first=Martin D. |title=Slovakia in History|title-link=Slovakia in History |date=2011 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |isbn=978-1-139-49494-6|language=en|doi=10.1017/CBO9780511780141|ref={{sfnref|Kamenec|2011a}}|pp=175\u2013192}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Longerich |first1=Peter |authorlink=Peter Longerich |title=Holocaust: The Nazi Persecution and Murder of the Jews |date=2010 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-280436-5 |language=en |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|entry=Slovakia|last1=Rothkirchen|first1=Livia|authorlink=Livia Rothkirchen|pp=595\u2013600 |editor1-last=Laqueur |editor1-first=Walter |editor2-last=Baumel |editor2-first=Judith Tydor |title=Holocaust Encyclopedia |date=2001 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |language=en|isbn=978-0-300-08432-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Silberklang |first1=David |title=Gates of Tears: the Holocaust in the Lublin District |date=2013 |publisher=Yad Vashem |location=Jerusalem |isbn=978-965-308-464-3 |language=English|title-link=Gates of Tears: the Holocaust in the Lublin District |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1 |first1=Lenka |title=Finale der Vernichtung: die Einsatzgruppe H in der Slowakei 1944/1945|title-link=Finale der Vernichtung |date=2013 |publisher=[[Wissenschaftliche Buchgesellschaft]] |location=Darmstadt |isbn=978-3-534-73733-8 |language=de|ref={{sfnref|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Sokolovi\u010d|first=Peter|title=Hlinkova Garda 1938 \u2013 1945|trans-title=Hlinka Guard 1938 \u2013 1945 |date=2013 |publisher=[[National Memory Institute (Slovakia)|National Memory Institute]]|location=Bratislava |isbn=978-80-89335-10-7 |url=https://www.upn.gov.sk/publikacie_web/hlinkova-garda.pdf|ref=harv|language=sk}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Ward |first1=James Mace |title=Priest, Politician, Collaborator: Jozef Tiso and the Making of Fascist Slovakia |date=2013|location=Ithaka |publisher=[[Cornell University Press]] |isbn=978-0-8014-6812-4 |language=en |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia |editor1-last=Miron |editor1-first=Gai |editor2-last=Shulhani |editor2-first=Shlomit |title=The Yad Vashem Encyclopedia of the Ghettos During the Holocaust |date=2009 |publisher=Yad Vashem |location=Jerusalem |volume =2|isbn=978-965-308-345-5 |ref={{sfnref|Yad Vashem|2009}} |language=en|entry=Opole|pp=550\u2013552}}\n{{refend}}\n\n====Journals====\n{{refbegin|35em|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=B\u00fcchler |first1=Yehoshua|authorli